   <text:h text:style-name="Heading_20_2" text:outline-level="2"><text:soft-page-break/>Interpretazione probabilistica.</text:h>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">In questo paragrafo riprenderemo i concetti introdotti nella seconda scheda per applicarli all’elettrone.</text:p>
   <text:p text:style-name="Standard">Una particella materiale, dal punto di vista della Meccanica Quantistica, è considerata come un sistema fisico sul quale è possibile effettuare misure di posizione. Quando eseguiamo una tale misura, il risultato in generale non è certo, ma è aleatorio. Quindi abbiamo una distribuzione di probabilità <draw:frame draw:style-name="fr15" draw:name="Object30" text:anchor-type="as-char" svg:width="0.3311in" svg:height="0.2055in" draw:z-index="18"><draw:object>
      <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block">
       <semantics>
        <mrow>
         <mstyle mathsize="12pt">
          <mrow>
           <mi>p</mi>
           <mrow>
            <mo fence="true" form="prefix" stretchy="true">(</mo>
            <mrow>
             <mi>x</mi>
            </mrow>
            <mo fence="true" form="postfix" stretchy="true">)</mo>
           </mrow>
          </mrow>
         </mstyle>
         <mrow/>
        </mrow>
        <annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{p left (x right )} {}</annotation>
       </semantics>
      </math>
     </draw:object><draw:image>
      <office:binary-data>AQAJAAAD1QAAAAIAFQAAAAAABQAAAAkCAAAAAAQAAAACAQEABQAAAAEC////AAQAAAAuARgA
       BQAAADECAQAAAAUAAAALAgAAAAAFAAAADAJgAqADEgAAACYGDwAaAP////8AABAAAADA////
       t////2ADAAAXAgAACwAAACYGDwAMAE1hdGhUeXBlAABgABAAAAD7Arz9CQEAAAAAkAEAAAAC
       BAIAEFN5bWJvbAACBAAAAC0BAAAIAAAAMgqeAV0BAQAAACgAEAAAAPsCvP0JAQAAAACQAQAA
       AAIEAgAQU3ltYm9sAAIEAAAALQEBAAQAAADwAQAACAAAADIKngHlAgEAAAApABUAAAD7AkD+
       AAAAAAAAkAEBAAAABAIAEFRpbWVzIE5ldyBSb21hbgAAgwQAAAAtAQAABAAAAPABAQAIAAAA
       MgqgAQACAQAAAHgACAAAADIKoAFxAAEAAABwAAoAAAAmBg8ACgD/////AQAAAAAAEAAAAPsC
       FAAJAAAAAAC8AgAAAAABAgIiU3lzdGVtAAAEAAAALQEBAAQAAADwAQAAAwAAAAAA
      </office:binary-data>
     </draw:image>
    </draw:frame><text:s/>per la variabile <text:span text:style-name="T8">x</text:span>. Come abbiamo detto nella scheda due, le probabilità possono essere ottenute come i moduli quadrati di certi numeri complessi detti ampiezze di probabilità. Quindi abbiamo una certa funzione complessa <draw:frame draw:style-name="fr15" draw:name="Object31" text:anchor-type="as-char" svg:width="0.3402in" svg:height="0.2055in" draw:z-index="19"><draw:object>
      <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block">
       <semantics>
        <mrow>
         <mstyle mathsize="12pt">
          <mrow>
           <mi>ψ</mi>
           <mrow>
            <mo fence="true" form="prefix" stretchy="true">(</mo>
            <mrow>
             <mi>x</mi>
            </mrow>
            <mo fence="true" form="postfix" stretchy="true">)</mo>
           </mrow>
          </mrow>
         </mstyle>
         <mrow/>
        </mrow>
        <annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{ψ left (x right )} {}</annotation>
       </semantics>
      </math>
     </draw:object><draw:image>
      <office:binary-data>AQAJAAAD7QAAAAIAFQAAAAAABQAAAAkCAAAAAAQAAAACAQEABQAAAAEC////AAQAAAAuARgA
       BQAAADECAQAAAAUAAAALAgAAAAAFAAAADAJgAqADEgAAACYGDwAaAP////8AABAAAADA////
       t////2ADAAAXAgAACwAAACYGDwAMAE1hdGhUeXBlAABgABAAAAD7Arz9CQEAAAAAkAEAAAAC
       BAIAEFN5bWJvbAACBAAAAC0BAAAIAAAAMgqeAXIBAQAAACgAEAAAAPsCvP0JAQAAAACQAQAA
       AAIEAgAQU3ltYm9sAAIEAAAALQEBAAQAAADwAQAACAAAADIKngH6AgEAAAApABUAAAD7AkD+
       AAAAAAAAkAEBAAAABAIAEFRpbWVzIE5ldyBSb21hbgAAoQQAAAAtAQAABAAAAPABAQAIAAAA
       MgqgARUCAQAAAHgAEAAAAPsCQP4AAAAAAACQAQEAAAIEAgAQU3ltYm9sAAIEAAAALQEBAAQA
       AADwAQAACAAAADIKoAH6/wEAAAB5AAoAAAAmBg8ACgD/////AQAAAAAAEAAAAPsCFAAJAAAA
       AAC8AgAAAAABAgIiU3lzdGVtAAAEAAAALQEAAAQAAADwAQEAAwAAAAAA
      </office:binary-data>
     </draw:image>
    </draw:frame><text:span text:style-name="T8"><text:s/></text:span>e la probabilità è data da<draw:frame draw:style-name="fr15" draw:name="Object32" text:anchor-type="as-char" svg:width="0.9217in" svg:height="0.2264in" draw:z-index="20"><draw:object>
      <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block">
